Sadly, in a number of interviews we find a strong disconnect between statements from the family, as they appeared into the news in The Netherlands, and the later case description of Betzaida Pitti, which can be partly explained by the fact that for logical reasons the police was unwilling to reveal the information they had and were working on at that moment.

00:21:41.840 --> 00:22:03.240
In their book 'Still Lost in Panama' the authors Christian Hardinghaus and Annette Ninner provide a very detailed report on the red truck story, which definitely contains sufficient connections to the case of Kris and Lisanne to be taken serious, and contrary to Martijn's statement there is every indication that the police did not easily dismiss these sightings.

00:22:04.400 --> 00:22:16.960
The red pickup truck was seen by Oliva and several other witnesses driving down from the Pianista trail around 16:00 on April 1, with its trunk filled with branches, and then, once again, in a similar situation on April 3.

00:22:18.000 --> 00:22:35.680
Police officers manage to establish the red truck is owned by a woman, who lives about 500 meters from the language school Spanish by the River. She states however that she did not drive the truck herself, and that on April 1 the truck was probably rented to the Feria de las Flores flower fair.

00:22:37.280 --> 00:22:53.560
When interviewed by the police, the owner of the flower fair confirms this, stating that the red truck was rented on April 1 between 11:45 and 17:00 to collect mosses, bromelias, foilage, and ferns from two cabins on the upper part of the Pianista trail.

00:22:55.120 --> 00:23:05.960
Although these times roughly coincide with the times that Kris and Lisanne walked up the mountain, the police does not find any further evidence linking the case of the missing girls with the red truck.

00:23:07.880 --> 00:23:26.160
On May 16th there is a first hint as to why all previous searches up to that moment have found nothing, when the Panamanian civil defense organisation SINAPROC receives a tip that two bodies have been seen by one of the locals in a remote area of the Culebra river between the two cable bridges, far to the north of the present search area.

00:23:27.640 --> 00:23:37.960
Due to the rainy season and the bad weather, this area is nearly impossible to reach though, and a helicopter which is send out to check fails to get close and low enough to get a good visual on the spot.

00:23:39.240 --> 00:23:53.800
It takes two full days before SINAPROC searchers finally manage to get within sight of the area, but if there were any bodies than by that time they have probably been washed away by the river again, and nothing is found.

00:23:55.520 --> 00:24:06.840
A few days later, there is another report that a helicopter noticed bodies floating in the Culebra river far down stream of the previous area, but once again by the time search teams arrive, nothing can be found.

00:24:10.440 --> 00:24:24.320
Sadly, with the rainy season now in full swing, the high water levels make a detailed search of the shores of the Culebra river too dangerous, and the sightings of bodies floating in the river are treated as just another false alarm.

00:26:40.960 --> 00:27:07.160
From May 25 till June 4 a special dutch teams of 12 dogs and 18 handlers joins the search for Kris and Lisanne. These dogs, which are specially trained to find immobilized persons, were originally ready to fly to Panama on April 7 but at that moment the dutch authorities did not yet see the need to use these dogs in the search, an opinion they changed only after a special request by the parents and media.

00:27:09.920 --> 00:27:15.720
At 7 a.m., rescue dogs and RHW escorts gathered in Duiven.

00:27:15.920 --> 00:27:21.760
It was a huge situation to get permission to get the sniffer dogs into Panama.

00:27:21.960 --> 00:27:29.160
We've been working on it for three days, and we've had 983 calls and commitments in the last four days.

00:27:29.360 --> 00:27:34.160
The rescue team was able to bring 12 rescue dogs and 18 escorts.

00:27:36.400 --> 00:27:40.360
Check in this afternoon for their flight to the South American country.

00:27:40.600 --> 00:27:45.920
The dogs begin their search in Boquete, the place where the girls disappeared in early April.

00:27:46.320 --> 00:27:51.960
Since then, no trace has been found, so the dogs leave late, but it certainly doesn't have to be too late.

00:27:52.160 --> 00:27:58.880
We can always find people, but we have found people who were gone for more than six months.

00:27:59.040 --> 00:28:03.960
The fact that these dogs are going there now is very good for the family and you can see that.

00:28:04.160 --> 00:28:08.320
It's a real revival, and it's bringing strength and energy.

00:28:08.440 --> 00:28:11.640
And everybody thinks, okay, we're going to do it again.

00:28:11.800 --> 00:28:17.320
In Panama, the girls were searched with dogs, but they were so-called "ruin dogs".

00:28:17.560 --> 00:28:20.240
Dogs that can only report living people.

00:28:20.600 --> 00:28:25.400
Our dogs are searching for both dead and living people.

00:28:25.960 --> 00:28:27.920
What do you expect from the search?

00:28:28.800 --> 00:28:29.800
I hope so.

00:28:30.320 --> 00:28:31.360
Is that a good chance?

00:28:31.640 --> 00:28:32.920
I say fifty percent.

00:28:33.400 --> 00:28:36.480
If we're in the right area, we should be able to do it.

00:28:36.480 --> 00:28:38.480
I hope you find them.

00:28:41.480 --> 00:28:56.960
One of the first area's the dogs search is the Pianista trail and all slopes and surrounding area's, however to the dismay of the dutch handlers they are not allowed to go beyond the second stream on the Atlantic slopes, which marks the border between the David and Bocas del Torro region.

00:28:58.640 --> 00:29:11.520
According to SINAPROC the lower slopes have already been searched with dogs, and with the rainy season now in full swing the area closer to the main river is too dangerous, quite apart from the fact that the dogs will not be able to cross via one of the cable bridges.

00:29:13.640 --> 00:29:35.600
The dog handlers than ask whether transport by helicopter can be arranged, stating they are willing to camp out in the wild during the night if necessary, so they can search at least some of the lower slopes closer to the river, but sadly this request is denied, possibly because it would require permission from the Bocas del Torro district to deploy the search dogs in that area.

00:29:37.440 --> 00:29:55.520
Given that the earlier report of bodies being seen on the shores of the Culebra river was the main reason for these dogs to be send to Panama, the refusal of the Panamanian authorities to deploy the dogs on the Atlantic slopes hits hard on the handlers, and basically dooms the whole mission.

00:29:58.000 --> 00:30:07.640
What use is it to send these highly specialized dogs to Panama if you then refuse them access to the area where possible bodies were seen?

00:30:11.280 --> 00:30:20.600
Never the less, the handlers try to make the best of it, searching all trails within the area, as well as the houses of Feliciano and Miriam and several other buildings.

00:30:22.640 --> 00:30:27.640
An alert which remains unexplained is given a few days later, when they search the Pedra de Lino trail.

00:30:28.640 --> 00:30:44.640
On the top of the Pedra de Lino, de dogs detect a find. At this place there is not only a wide view across Boquete, but also a view toward the area where the white bag was found, and beyond, toward the Atlantic slopes.

00:30:45.600 --> 00:30:59.280
With the prevailing northerly winds and with the dogs being able to smell bodies over very large distances, it is not completely impossible that this was a genuine alert, but as they are not allowed to search the Atlantic slopes there is no way for the dog handlers to find out.

00:31:01.480 --> 00:31:14.280
In the remaining days the dogs are used to search the area of the Baru volcano, as well the Hidden Waterfalls and the Caldera hotsprings, while they are also used for a large number of house searches, all without any results though.

00:31:16.200 --> 00:31:37.160
The homes of all Dutch expats in Boquete are searched and during one such search, on June 2, military assistance is requested after a tip when one person is responding very aggressive, causing a Panamanian police officer to become injured. Although the home is found to contain a large number of knives and other weapons, no sign of Kris or Lisanne is found.

00:31:38.520 --> 00:32:03.360
On their final day in Panama, the dogs are used to search near an old hydro dam in the Caldera river, where once again the dogs indicate a find, this time halfway up a very steep slope. As the terrain is too steep to traverse, Panamanian experts are used to search the area, and later, after they are back in Holland, the team hears that two bodies have been found, an old man and a child who went missing several months ago.

00:32:04.520 --> 00:32:10.880
After the initial hope, the fact that the dogs fail to find any trace of the two girls falls very hard on the parents.

00:32:14.640 --> 00:32:29.600
On hindsight, the fact that the dogs were flown in very late, when the rainy season was already under way and crossing the rivers was too dangerous, together with the fact that the dogs were not allowed to operate within the Bocas del Torro district in the north is what doomed the expedition.

00:32:32.040 --> 00:32:41.720
Apart from the locals, barely anyone fully understands though how rough and desolate the terrain on the Atlantic slopes, north of the Mirador, truly is.

00:32:43.920 --> 00:32:59.120
Even those who occasionally walk the Pianista trail past the Mirador get barely more than a glimpse of what would be waiting for them should they go off the trail. An inexperienced person, moving off trail through terrain such as this will not stand a chance.

00:33:01.480 --> 00:33:13.600
Sadly, more than anything else it is the failure of the media to show the real magnitude of the wilderness north of the Mirador which gives rise to the growing number of foul play theories.

00:33:16.280 --> 00:33:33.000
Week after week, people are shown cozy scene's from the streets of Boquete, or the reasonable benign terrain just outside the city, where there are lots of farms and cabins, and when the search teams fail to find any trace of the girls the logical conclusion is quickly reached that they must have fallen prey to foul play.

00:33:35.120 --> 00:33:46.880
Hampered by bureaucracy and their rigid district borders, SINAPROC concentrates their searches on the Pacific slopes of the David area, secretly well aware that a search on the Atlantic slopes will not stand a chance

00:33:49.000 --> 00:34:00.520
Even if they had ten times as many search teams and dogs, a search of the forests on the Atlantic slopes would take many months, and it would be a very dangerous undertaking, certainly during the rainy season..

00:34:02.640 --> 00:34:15.120
Once the torrential rains start though, huge quantities of water wash down these slopes, and anything lost in the forest eventually flushes down into the Culebra river. Which is indeed exactly what happens.

00:34:31.239 --> 00:34:47.159
The best SINAPROC can do is overfly the rivers and the open paddocks with helicopters, but if Kris and Lisanne went beyond the Mirador and they left the trail for some reason, the chances of finding them in the forests is close to zero.

00:34:50.679 --> 00:35:01.280
Sadly, at that time this harsh reality is mostly lost on the parents and the media, as very few people have any real perception of what the terrain beyond the Mirador looks like.

00:36:39.360 --> 00:37:02.760
On June 11, 71 days after Kris and Lisanne went missing, Irma the wife of a local farmer from Alto Romero, walks down to the Culebra river to wash herself after working all day on the fields. That day the water is slightly lower than it has been during the past weeks, and in a shallow turn of the river, close to the shore, is a place where the current is less strong.

00:37:03.600 --> 00:37:15.160
When she goes down to the water, she spots an object dangling above the water stuck between a large boulder and some driftwood. When she walks over to take a better look, she finds a backpack, which she later shows to her husband.

00:37:15.880 --> 00:37:29.960
Inside the backpack, they find 2 mobile phones, a digital camera, 88 dollars and 30 cents, bras and sunglasses, as well as an insurance pass from Lisanne Froon, a little lock with a key, and an empty plastic water bottle.

00:37:30.640 --> 00:37:48.080
After ten long weeks there is finally some tangible evidence in the case of the missing girls, and as we will see in the next episode, a subsequent search along the river shore will turn up some more pieces of clothing and remains from both girls, leaving no doubt that both of them have died.

00:37:48.760 --> 00:38:03.480
Although the location of the backpack is well outside the search area of the teams from David, this area was searched earlier by locals and by a SINAPROC team from Bocas del Torro, which traveled the whole length of the Pianista trail, in both cases nothing was found.

00:38:04.080 --> 00:38:18.960
Due to consistent bad weather, it takes two days before a helicopter is able to deliver Betzaida Piti and other police and SINAPROC officials to Alto Romero, where they inspect the backpack as well as the place where this was found, before taking the backpack back with them for forensic analysis.

00:38:19.680 --> 00:38:41.080
Five years later, in the book 'Lost in the Jungle', Pitti will write a dramatic account how she became injured and seriously dehydrated during the long walk from Alto Romero to the river and how she feared she would not make it back alive, however perhaps more surprising is the fact that she instantly halts all further investigations into a possible crime against the two girls.

00:38:41.720 --> 00:38:59.280
According to her own report, at the moment the backpack was found, Pitti was planing a major action after a tip that a man in the Renacimiento District was involved in the kidnapping of Kris and Lisanne, but once the backpack was found she concluded that the tip had to be false, and canceled all further searches and investigations.

00:38:59.840 --> 00:39:16.240
During an interview, Pitti is said to have remarked that Kris and Lisanne were unhappy in Boquete and perhaps tried to walk back to Bocas del Torro via the Pianista trail, revering to the theory from several of the locals that the two girls had drowned after falling down one of the cable bridges.

00:39:16.960 --> 00:39:29.280
Apparently the main purpose of the Panamanian authorities was to find the two girls, and once the backpack and a few of their remains were recovered, this task was accomplished and the case was closed.

00:39:29.840 --> 00:39:40.400
This weird and highly controversial decision has haunted this case till this very day, giving rise to an ever growing number of ever wilder theories.

00:39:40.920 --> 00:39:58.520
In any normal crime investigation, one would expect that the discovery of remains and major evidence like the backpack would given an extra impulse to the investigation, with a major effort to solve this case and use the new evidence to find the perpetrator, but this never happened.

00:39:59.040 --> 00:40:08.920
And as this never happened, it is not surprising at all that hundreds of others decided to start their own research and promote their own theory, trying to solve a case which was never properly closed.

00:40:09.480 --> 00:40:24.520
As we will see in the next episode of this series, the parents of Kris and Lisanne weren't happy with this outcome either, and rightfully started their own investigation as well, although in the end they too failed to find a complete answer to all remaining questions.

